Lebanon's comprehensive crisis
Beirut — — Looking back, financial crises usually seem to have omens before they happen; however, they rarely clearly indicate the course of history.
The situation in Lebanon is the same now, a predictable crisis has plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been sustained by external borrowing, which inevitably led to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, foreign capital inflow had to stop. This point arrived at the end of 2019, followed by a series of negative shocks.
This "sudden stop" of capital brought the country severe triple crises.
The first problem is the international balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit is as high as 25% of its GDP, with a too small export base that cannot even afford the costs of necessary imports.
The second problem is the fiscal one.
Lebanon's public debt now exceeds 150% of its GDP.
Government revenue is collapsing under the heavy pressure of economic recession, with a large budget deficit, already 10% of GDP in 2019 and still rapidly expanding.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
The main banks, as the primary recipients of foreign capital inflows, have invested heavily in Lebanese sovereign debt (average 50% of their investment portfolios), and are now essentially insolvent.
These crises together have pushed Lebanon's economy into a deep abyss.
Companies that crave loans and imports have begun to lay off employees or completely shut down.
Economic recession may lead to a Great Depression in Lebanon.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but expatriates, who are attracted to high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate tied to the US dollar.
It's no surprise to see signs of the "Dutch disease" everywhere: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect and lowering the national savings rate to an unlikely level of 3% of GDP.
Income inequality is very high and rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the actual (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, significantly weakening tradable sectors.
Due to a lack of export goods and services, Lebanon has been losing educated young people.
More importantly, large-scale capital inflows have allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their power through patronage rather than performance.
These elites have extracted wealth from both the public and private sectors, establishing a bloated patronage-based ruling group.
Although this has ensured political stability in an otherwise chaotic region, it has failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply has been intermittent and unreliable, and the broader macroeconomic challenges have been completely ignored.
Financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolution movement took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Despite this, the government's response to Lebanon's economic problems has so far been overwhelmingly biased towards the elite, indicating that this crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle classes, and further consolidate sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the main shareholders of each bank, including politicians in power, to decide how to ration cash withdrawals.
In fact, this allowed the elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens found it difficult to access deposits.
The central bank has lowered deposit interest rates but not public debt interest rates, thus increasing bank profits.
Despite a continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to service its foreign debt mainly owed to domestic banks.
There are indications that it may start selling state assets to elite-connected entities at fire-sale prices.
At the same time, the formal exchange rate remains unchanged, with the elite allowed to obtain dollars at low exchange rates, while ordinary citizens face the reality of a rapidly depreciating free market exchange rate, which is currently 40% lower.
When the state starts printing pounds to pay civil servant salaries, depreciation will accelerate.
Actually, the central bank has been paying interest on dollar deposits in Lebanese pounds (dollar deposits account for more than 80% of all deposits), thereby creating conditions for inflation to eliminate public debt.
As the cost of debt reduction through "dollarization" of depositor equity is passed on to depositors, bank equity can essentially be spared.
If this becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle class will significantly decrease due to the reduction in actual wages and pensions, as well as the clearing of savings.
The emigration process of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the immigrant community – which this system relies on – will be damaged.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a system of poverty, which can be controlled by increasingly cheap shelters.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
Compared to this, the establishment of a new republic driven by revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance is far below its potential, and that achievements, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, cronyism, and inequality.
They hope to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural hub, and create more synergies with immigrant communities.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction in public debt, which will be secured by bank equity and force a reduction in deposits of more than 50% of total deposits by 1% depositors.
They support a moderate depreciation of the currency and a thorough improvement in the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek a deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices and increased spending on social projects and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The current infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is a part of the country's process of seeking new political solutions, and has generated even greater conflict.
Financial crisis poses a fatal threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
Lebanon's future remains uncertain.
